text: An ATP-dependent ligase catalyzes the fourth ring cyclization in tetracycline biosynthesis Wei Xu a, y a Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering, University of California, Los Angeles, United States b Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry, University of California, Los Angeles, United States Article history: Received 11 July 2015 Received in revised form 10 September 2015 Accepted 12 September 2015 Available online xxx Keywords: Tetracycline Biosynthesis Polyketide cyclase Claisen condensation Acyl-CoA ligase Tetracycline antibiotics are a well-known family of aromatic polyketides produced by the Streptomyces, which share a charac- teristic, linearly fused tetracyclic framework (Fig. 1). Both oxytet- racycline (1) and chlorotetracycline (2) were front-line antibiotics that display broad-spectrum antibacterial activities.1,2 Semi- synthetic derivatives of tetracyclines have continued to be discov- tetracycline resistance, ered to overcome known modes of suggesting this remains a privileged scaffold for antibiotics dis- covery.3,4 SF2575 (3) produced by Streptomyces sp. SF2575 is a richly decorated member in the tetracycline family and displays potent anticancer activities.5 The tetracyclic backbone of all members of this family is derived from an unreduced polyketide chain syn- thesized by a type II polyketide synthase (PKS), followed by addi- tional post-PKS tailoring modiﬁcations including regioselective cyclization. The biosynthetic gene clusters of some naturally oc- curring tetracycline natural products have been discovered and mapped in recent years, including those of 1e3, dactylocycline (4) and chelocardin (5) (Fig. 1A, Fig. S1).6e11 Using the gene cluster information, especially that of 1, most of the biosynthetic steps in tetracycline biosynthesis have been elucidated.8,12e18 address: yitang@ucla.edu (Y. Tang).

Tel.: þ1 310 825 0375; fax: þ1 310 206 4107; e-mail These authors contributed equally to this work. , Peng Wang a, Yi Tang a, b, * j o u r n a l h o m e p a g e : w w w . e l s e v i e r . c o m / l o c a t e / t e t Cyclization steps in biosynthesis of aromatic polyketides are typically directed by speciﬁc enzymes known as cyclases. The fourth ring cyclization step that forms the fully aromatic pretetramid during tetracycline biosynthesis has not been resolved. Herein we report in vitro and in vivo studies on the fourth ring cyclization step in biosynthesis of SF2575 and related tetracyclic natural products. We demonstrate that an enzyme belonging to the ATP-dependent acyl-CoA ligase family catalyzes the C1eC18 Claisen condensation step that forms the A ring and yields the linear, tetracyclic aromatic compound that is the precursor to tetracyclic natural products. The enzyme, SsfL2, is well-conserved in all tetracycline biosynthetic gene clusters discovered to date. It is proposed that SsfL2 directly adenylates the tricyclic carboxylic acid to facilitate the ﬁnal carbon-carbon bond formation, and coenzyme A is not required. The biosynthesis of tetracyclines starts with the assembly of the decaketide backbone by the minimal PKS (Fig. 1B), which consists of the ketosynthase (KS or KSa)-chain length factor (CLF, also known as KSb) heterodimer, an acyl-carrier protein (ACP) that is posttranslationally modiﬁed at the active site serine with a phos- phopantetheinyl arm, and the malonyl-CoA:ACP acyltransferase (MAT)19 shared with fatty acid synthase. In tetracycline bio- synthetic pathways, the starter unit is most frequently malonamyl- CoA, which is modiﬁed from malonyl-CoA. In the absence of the malonamyl starter unit, acetate unit derived from decarboxylation of malonyl-CoA can prime the minimal PKS, as seen in 5.11,17 Fol- lowing complete assembly of the poly-b-ketone backbone, speciﬁc cyclases are required to regioselectively cyclize the backbone to yield pretetramid 6 and prevent formation of spontaneous shunt products that can form from the reactive backbone.20 The four sequential steps required to form 6 are ﬁrst ring (C7eC12 aldol), second ring (C5eC14 aldol), third ring (C3eC16 aldol) and fourth ring (C1eC18 Claisen) cyclizations (Fig. 1B). The enzymes responsible for ﬁrst (D) and second (C) ring cyclizations have been identiﬁed in both oxy and ssf pathways, which are SsfY1 and SsfY2, respectively in the biosynthesis of SF2575.9 The third (B) ring is proposed to close spontaneously to afford the tricyclic in- termediate 7, which can be hydrolyzed off the ACP to yield the carboxylic acid 8. Previous reconstitution work with related path- ways have shown that inclusion of the ﬁrst and second ring cyclases with the minimal decaketide PKS can lead to formation of oxidized (cid:1) 2015 Elsevier Ltd. B) the biosynthesis of tetracyclic framework indicated with enzymes from the SF2575 pathway. derivative of 8, which are homologues of the well-known aklanonic acid.21 In contrast to these well-characterized steps, the enzymatic basis for the Claisen cyclization that furnishes the fourth (A) ring cyclization in tetracycline biosynthesis is not resolved. This step was suggested to happen spontaneously in our previous study, however, solid experimental evidence has been lacking.12 In the cyclization of other four-ring aromatic polyketides, such as the precursors of tetracenomycin and anthracyclines, dedicated fourth ring cyclases are found in each gene cluster.22e26 Although these enzymes catalyze cyclizations of different regioselectivity to that which is required here, these studies point to an enzymatic step in forming the A ring in tetracycline as well. In this study, we show that this step is catalyzed by an enzyme belonging to the ATP- dependent acyl-CoA ligase enzyme in the oxy and ssf pathways. This enzyme is found in all tetracycline biosynthetic gene clusters, indicating a conserved function in these pathways. 2. Results and discussion

Our search for the fourth ring cyclase initiated with our previous heterologous reconstitution studies involving the oxy and ssf pathways. In the bottoms-up reconstitution of SF2575 biosynthesis in Streptomyces lividans K4-114, we had found that inclusion of SsfL2, an acyl-CoA ligase like enzyme, is required to form the tet- racycline intermediate 6-methylpretetramid 9 (in the presence of other required enzymes, Fig. 3).9 Absence of SsfL2 led to the for- mation of the anthraquinone WJ83Q2 (10).12 Homologs of SsfL2 are found in other tetracycline biosynthetic gene clusters including OxyH in oxy pathway and DacH in dac pathway. This result led us to revisit our previous bottoms-up reconstituted oxy pathway in Streptomyces coelicolor CH999, which was reported to produce the tetracyclic product WJ83T1 (11). The involved plasmid pWJ83 was fully re-sequenced and it indeed carries a copy of oxyH, most likely Please cite this article in press as: Xu, W.; et al., Tetrahedron (2015), http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2015.09.029 W. Xu et al. / Tetrahedron xxx (2015) 1e6 as a result of the original cloning strategy (however was not re- ported in the manuscript). These results indicated that SsfL2 and OxyH are intricately involved in the formation of the A ring in tetracycline pathways. Acyl-CoA ligase family of enzymes catalyze a two-step reaction: the ﬁrst step is the ATP-dependent adenylation of the free acid into the acyl-AMP; the second step is the trans- esteriﬁcation of the activated acyl substrate to form the acyl-CoA. No member of this family has been implicated as a polyketide cy- clase, hence additional genetic and biochemical experiments are required to conﬁrm the proposed roles of these enzymes.

To probe the function of SsfL2, we deleted the ssfL 2 gene from the cosmid-based SF2575 over-producing heterologous host S. liv- idans K4-114.10,27 Elimination of ssfL2 completely abolished pro- duction of SF2575 and did not yield any previously identiﬁed tetracyclic intermediates. Instead, the host/vector pair produced þ a new intermediate 12 (UV lmax¼368 nm, [MþH] m/z¼400) (Fig. 2, trace ii, Fig. S3). Similarly, we deleted oxyH from the cosmid- based oxytetracycline producing S. lividans K4-114 host/vector system. The resulting strain was also incapable of producing 1 and showed an identical metabolic proﬁle to that of the ssfL2 knockout strain (Fig. 2, trace i). Unfortunately, attempts to isolate 12 were unsuccessful due to its instability during puriﬁcation. However, observation of the same compound 12 from two tetracycline pathways, together with spectrum information of compounds isolated from oxy reconstitution studies, led us to propose 12 to be a tricyclic compound as shown in Fig. 3. The proposed C-ring in 12 is identical that of WJ119 (13), a four-ring shunt product previously isolated in study of oxy cluster. The lower lmax in 12 (368 nm vs 435 nm for 13) also suggests that 12 is a tricyclic compound.12 12 can be derived from 8 by the C-ring speciﬁc methyltransferase presented in both gene clusters (OxyF or SsfM4), followed by spontaneous C-ring oxidation. To further verify the role of SsfL2, we performed genetic complementation of ssfL2 in the aforementioned deletion strain. As shown in Fig. 2 (trace iii), production of 3 was restored, thus conﬁrming that the abolishment of 3 in trace ii was solely due to the absence of SsfL2. These studies established that the acyl-CoA ligase homologs SsfL2 and OxyH are essential for SF2575

These studies established that the acyl-CoA ligase homologs SsfL2 and OxyH are essential for SF2575 and oxytetracycline biosynthesis, respectively, and are di- rectly involved in cyclization of the fourth ring en route to 6 and 9.9 We next performed mix-and-match experiments between the oxy and ssf pathways in order to demonstrate the function of SsfL2 and OxyH are the same. We also intended to examine if the putative new fourth ring cyclase requires the terminal amide for the Claisen cyclization. To do so, we cotransformed S. lividans K4-114 with pWJ83c, which encodes OxyABC (minimal PKS), OxyJ (C-9 re- ductase), OxyKN (D and C ring cyclases) with a new plasmid (pLP194) that expresses SsfL2. The host/vector pair K4-114/pWJ83c produces the tricyclic desmethylaklanonic acid 14 (Fig. 4, trace i).12 However, LC-MS analysis of the extract of the doubly transformed K4 strain revealed emergence of a very hydrophobic compound 15 with a similar retention time (Fig. 4, trace iii) and almost identical UV spectrum when compared to WJ83T1 11 (lmax¼498 nm vs 500 nm for 11, also see Supplementary data, Fig. S4).12 Given the difference in mass between 15 and 11 (the molecular weight of 15 is one m.u. less than that of 11), the structure of 15 is concluded to must be the acetyl-version of 11 as shown in Fig. 3. To further conﬁrm that no other Streptomyces enzyme is in- volved in fourth ring cyclization step and to probe the catalytic mechanism, we performed in vitro assays using puriﬁed SsfL2 expressed from Escherichia coli BL21(DE3). When 14 was used as substrate, no conversion to the corresponding four-ring products 15 was observed (Fig. 5, trace iv), which is in consistent with 14 being an oxidized shunt product. As the acetate primed tricyclic in- termediate 16 is prone to oxidation to yield 14 (Fig. 3), a direct in vitro assay was therefore not possible. To enable probing of SsfL2 activities in vitro, we reconstituted the entire minimal PKS and immediate tailoring enzymes to generate the tricyclic substrate 16 in situ. The oxy KS-CLF heterodimer was puriﬁed from S. lividans K4-114/pWJ131. The holo form of OxyC (ACP) was expressed and puriﬁed from E. coli BAP1.28 The S. coelicolor MAT,29 C9 ketor- eductase ActIII from the actinorhodin pathway,30 the C7eC12 ﬁrst ring cyclase Gris ARO/CYC from the griseusin pathway31 and the cognate second ring cyclase SsfY2 were expressed and puriﬁed from E. coli BL21(DE3). Fig. 5. In vitro assay of fourth ring cyclization. Assays were performed at room tem- perature in 100 mM Sodium Phosphate buffer pH 7.4, and 2 mM NADPH, with 10 mM OxyAB, 20 mM OxyC, 0.3 mM MAT, 20 mM ActIII, 20 mM Gris ARO/CYC and 50 mM SsfY2. i) Addition of 2 mM ATP, 10 mM MgCl2, 2 mM free CoA 2 mM malonyl-CoA and 50 mM SsfL2 yields compound 15; ii) omission of ATP from i) gives 13; iii) omission of CoA and CoA equivalent from i) still produces 15; iv) feeding 2 mM 14 to SsfL2 with ATP and CoA didn’t produce 15. enzymes. As reported previously,12 the combination of OxyAB, OxyC, MAT, ActIII, Gris ARO/CYC, and SsfY2 in presence of malonyl- CoA, and NADPH produced the anthraquinone 14, while no tetra- cyclic compounds were observed. In contrast, addition of SsfL2, ATP, MgCl2 and CoA to the previous assay led to formation of the tet- racyclic 15 (Fig. 5, trace i), which is oxidized from the expected product 17. Omission of ATP from the in vitro assay led to the production of 14, conﬁrming the ATP-dependence of SsfL2 (Fig. 5, trace ii).

Conﬁrmation of the activity and ATP-dependency of SsfL2 in the coupled PKS assay allows us to propose a reaction mechanism for this enzymatic conversion (Fig. 3). We suggest that the tricyclic carboxylic acid intermediate 8 (or 16) is the substrate and is formed upon hydrolysis from the ACP-bound thioester. SsfL2 activates 8 (or 16) by forming the corresponding adenylate 18 using ATP, which is a canonical reaction catalyzed by CoA ligase enzymes. We propose that 18 can then be directly cyclized via a Claisen-like condensation to cyclize the A-ring and afford 6 (or 17). Alternatively, as suggested by its function, the reactive 18 can also be transesteriﬁed to form the CoA thioester and the CoA serves as the leaving group in the Claisen condensation. In this mechanism, the hydrolysis of 7 fol- lowed by forming the CoA thioester appears to be a chemically futile cycle. To investigate the CoA dependence of SsfL2 function, we removed free CoA in the assay LCand substituted malonyl-CoA with pre-formed malonyl-S-OxyC. The substitution is necessary since free CoA will accumulate as malonyl-CoA is consumed in the PKS reaction. As shown in Fig. 5, trace iii, production of 15 is not abolished in absence of CoA, supporting the CoA independent mechanism that uses the better leaving group AMP.

The C1eC18 cyclization mode in tetracycline biosynthesis is identical to that during the formation of the fourth ring in the biosynthesis of aureolic acids.32,33 Indeed, homologs of SsfL2 that were annotated as acyl-CoA ligases are also found in the reported aureolic acid gene clusters, including MtmL from the mithramycin gene cluster,34 CmmLII from the chromomycin gene cluster35 and PokL from the polyketomycin gene cluster.36 (see Supplementary data, Table S3) To test whether a SsfL2 homolog from these clus- ters could also catalyze the C1eC18 cyclization reaction, we coex- pressed the gene encoding MtmL from Streptomyces argillaceus with those encoded in pWJ83c in S. lividans K4-114. As expected, the resulting strain also produces 15 (Fig. 4, trace ii), suggesting that MtmL is the fourth-ring cyclase in the mithramycin biosynthetic pathway, instead of the previously proposed MtmX.37 The surprising involvement of an enzyme bearing homology to the long chain acyl-CoA ligase family in the cyclization step is a new ﬁnding in bacterial polyketide biosynthesis. In contrast, enzymatic Please cite this article in press as: Xu, W.; et al., Tetrahedron (2015), http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2015.09.029 W. Xu et al. / Tetrahedron xxx (2015) 1e6

fourth ring cyclization in tetracenomycin and anthracycline bio- synthesis utilizes different enzymes and strategies. For example, TcmI in the tetracenomycin pathway catalyzes the C2eC19 ring closure and convert a tricyclic carboxylic acid Tcm F2 into tetracy- clic Tcm F1.22 The anthracycline fourth-ring cyclases, including DauD,24 DnrD,23 AknH25 and SnoaL26 from daunomycin, doxoru- bicin, aclacinomycin A and nogalamycin, respectively catalyzes C2eC19 ring closure of corresponding methyl esters (Fig. 6). In these examples, the fourth ring cyclizes through an intramolecular aldol addition/condensation between nucleophilic C2 and electro- philic C19. Both TcmI and SnoaL have a b-a-b fold core, and belong to the ferredoxin fold superfamily.22,26 The C1eC18 fourth ring cyclization steps in tetracycline and aureolic acid pathways are different in two aspects. First, C1eC18 cyclization is a Claisen-like condensation involves nucleophilic attack on the terminal car- boxyl, hence requiring a strong leaving group such as AMP. Second, positioning of the reacting functional groups in this reaction is different than that in the C2eC19 cyclization, therefore requiring a different binding mode between substrate and cyclase (Fig. 6). Fig. 6. Enzymatic fourth ring cyclization in biosynthesis of tetracenomycin, nogala- mycin and SF2575. In summary, we have veriﬁed in vivo and in vitro that an en- zyme belonging to the CoA ligase family catalyzes the ATP- dependent Claisen cyclization of the fourth ring during tetracy- cline and also likely aureolic acid biosynthesis. Interestingly, se- quence alignment of these SsfL2-like proteins with typical acyl-CoA ligase shows that they might have lost CoA binding sites (Fig. S5). Future examination of the active site of SsfL2 or related enzymes will yield additional insights into a possible substrate binding mode and catalytic mechanism.

4.1. Bacterial strains and DNA manipulation XL-1 Blue (Stratagene) was used for the manipulation of plasmid DNA. E. coli strain BL21(DE3) was used for protein expression. E. coli strain BAP1 was used for holo-ACP expression.28 Fosmid 11A12 and 5F15 were used as templates to amplify S. sp. SF2575 DNA by PCR. S. argillaceus genomic DNA was used to amplify mtmL. PCR fragments were cloned into pCR-Blunt vector obtained from Invitrogen and sequenced. All restriction enzymes were purchased from New En- gland Biolabs. PCR reagents for pfx DNA polymerase were pur- chased from Invitrogen. S. lividans strain K4-11427 was used at a host for the transformation of shuttle vector constructs. Pro- toplast preparation and PEG-mediated DNA transformation tech- niques were performed as published by Hopwood et al.38 4.2. Spectroscopic analysis NMR of compounds was obtained on a Bruker DRX500 at the University of California Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry NMR facility. LC-MS spectra were obtained on a Shimadzu 2010 EV Liquid Chromatography Mass Spectrometer using positive and negative electrospray ionization and a Phenomenex Luna 5 m 2.0(cid:2)100 mm C18 reverse-phase column. Samples were separated on a linear gradient of 5e95% CH3CN in water (0.05% formic acid) for 30 min at a ﬂow rate of 0.1 mL/min. 4.3. Preparation and puriﬁcation of 15

For isolation of 15, S. lividans K4-114/pWJ83c/pLP194 was pre- cultured in 50 mL of R5 liquid media (25 mg/L thiostrepton, 50 mg/L apramycin) in a 250 mL bafﬂed Erlenmeyer ﬂask at 30 (cid:3)C and 250 rpm for 3 days. 1 mL of pre-cultures were inoculated on plates (3 L) of R5 agar (25 mg/L thiostrepton, 50 mg/L apramycin) in 150 mm(cid:2)10 mm Petri dishes and incubated at 30 (cid:3)C for 10 days. The cultured agar was harvested and extracted with the same volume of ethyl acetate twice. Organic solvent was dried in vacuo. The crude extract was partitioned with hexane:methanol 1:1. The methanol layer containing 15 was dried and the resulting extract was resuspended in chloroform and further partitioned with a 1:1 chloroform:water. The chloroform fraction was collected and dried. The pellet was resuspended in methanol and centrifuged for 5 min at 4000 g. The methanol insoluble pellet containing 15 was resus- pended by sonication in 5 mL chloroform:methanol 1:1 and the soluble portion was loaded on a Sephadex column containing w30 g GE Healthcare LH20 Sephadex resin equilibrated in 1:1 chloroform:methanol as a mobile phase. Pure 15 was obtained after fractionating twice by Sephadex column. 4.4. Expression and puriﬁcation of recombinant enzymes

For expression in E. coli, target genes were cloned into a pET28 vector with an N-terminal His tag. Most proteins were expressed in E. coli BL21(DE3) strain. E. coli BAP1 was used for expression of holo- OxyC. For each enzyme, a 5 mL overnight culture transformed with expression plasmid was grown in LB medium containing 35 mg/L kanamycin. This overnight culture was used to inoculate a 500 mL ﬂask of LB containing 35 mg/L kanamycin. Cultures were grown at 37 (cid:3)C until OD600 of 0.5 at which point IPTG was added to a ﬁnal concentration of 120 mM to induce protein expression. The induced cultures were further shaken overnight at 16 (cid:3)C. Protein puriﬁcation was carried out at 4 (cid:3)C. Cell pellets were resuspended in Buffer A (50 mM TriseHCl, pH 7.9, 10 mM imidazole and 50 mM NaCl). Cells were disrupted by sonication. The crude cell lysate was centrifuged at 16,000 rpm and the soluble fraction was collected and incubated with Ni-NTA resin (Qiagen) for 2 h with gentle mixing. Protein-resin mixture was added to a gravity ﬂow column and buffers containing increasing step gradients of imid- azole were applied. The target proteins were eluted in Buffer A containing 250 mM imidazole. A proper cutoff Amicon ﬁltration column (Millipore) was used for buffer exchange and concentration of the protein solution. Puriﬁed enzymes were stored in Buffer B (50 mM TriseHCl pH 7.9, 2 mM EDTA, 2 mM DTT). Proteins were aliquoted, ﬂash frozen and stored at (cid:4)80 (cid:3)C. Protein concentrations were measured by Bradford assay using bovine serum albumin (BSA) as a standard.39

All in vitro assays were performed with the following conditions unless otherwise speciﬁed: 100 mM Sodium Phosphate buffer pH 7.4, 2 mM ATP, 10 mM MgCl2, 2 mM malonyl-CoA, 2 mM NADPH. Enzyme concentrations used were: 10 mM OxyAB, 20 mM OxyC, 0.3 mM MAT, 20 mM ActIII, 20 mM Gris ARO/CYC. 50 mM SsfY2, and 50 mM SsfL2. Reaction mixture was incubated at room temperature overnight. A 100 mL reaction was extracted with 200 mL ethyl ace- tate (1% acetic acid). Organic phase was then collected dried ed in vacuo. Samples were then resuspended in 30 mL methanol and analyzed by HPLC or LCMS as described in Spectroscopic analysis. 4.6. Heterologous biosynthesis of polyketides using S. lividans S. lividans K4-114 strain27 transformed with different constructs were grown on R5 agar plus 25 mg/mL thiostrepton and 50 mg/mL apramycin if required. Cultures were grown at 30 (cid:3)C for approxi- mately one week until colonies were well formed. For HPLC anal- ysis, colonies were streaked out on 40 mL of fresh R5 agar (plus 25 mg/mL thiostrepton and 50 mg/mL apramycin if required) and incubated for 7e10 days until the plate was well pigmented. The agar was then ﬁnely chopped and extracted with 40 mL organic solvent (99% ethyl acetate, 1% acetic acid). Sodium sulfate was added to the extract to remove residual water, and the solvent was evaporated and the products were resuspended in 400 mL metha- nol. The extracts were analyzed by LCMS. Compounds were iden- tiﬁed by matching retention time and UV spectra to authentic standards.
